<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="163" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="163">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="163">
With the mixture of gently clavate and ventricose cystidia alongside the strongly dextrinoid basidiospores, this species belongs within 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma subsp. sect." order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="section" section="Velutipes" species="glauca" subSpecies="sect.">Hebeloma sect. Velutipes</taxonomicName>
. Within this section the combination of spores with minimum average width 7.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
and a distinctly loosening perispore in at least some spores, together with the absence of pleurocystidia, defines this species. The collection of 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. neurophyllum" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="neurophyllum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. neurophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Mexico, gathered at El Ranchito in Chihuahua, matches well with other collections of this species. We are not aware of any synonyms for this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="163">
In terms of ITS, the most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. neurophyllum" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="neurophyllum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. neurophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. celatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="celatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. celatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. erebium" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="erebium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. erebium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. quercetorum" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="quercetorum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. quercetorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the ITS sequences of which were around 99% similar (99.2-98.6%) to those of 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. neurophyllum" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="neurophyllum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. neurophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="G. F. Atk., Annales Mycologici 7 (4): 370" authorityYear="1909" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma neurophyllum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="neurophyllum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">Hebeloma neurophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to correspond to UNITE SH1733487.08FU (99%). Intriguingly, this species hypothesis includes a number of soil sample sequences from Estonia, suggesting that either 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. neurophyllum" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="neurophyllum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. neurophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in Europe, too, or that species known to occur in Europe also contain ITS copies corresponding to 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. neurophyllum" pageId="0" pageNumber="163" rank="species" species="neurophyllum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="163">H. neurophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
below the detection limit of Sanger sequencing.
</paragraph>
